host_about:
I'm a Southerner by birth (born in NC, grew up in Memphis) but have been in San Francisco and working in Silicon Valley for over 20 years. My husband, Nick, is a OB/GYN. He's off to Budapest for a year because he was recently awarded a Fulbright to study home birth in Hungary and Prezi is headquartered there. I'll be visiting him frequently, so why not.  

To be honest, we're a little nervous about renting out our home, because it is just that: our home. Two renovations and twenty years of futzing and we've got it exactly where we want it--to live and to retire. Fortunately, all remodeling choices were to made with the goal of sharing our home with our family and friends. I guess now we're just extending that circle a little further.

neighborhood_overview:
We live in one of the most beautiful and safest areas of San Francisco. Our neighborhood is really two neighborhoods: Cow Hollow and Marina.

Cow Hollow has two main streets, Fillmore (1 block away) and Union Streets, with everything from casual take-out to fine dining, coffee shops, bars, fitness studios, clothing and grocery stores.

Heading north across the street (on Lombard) and up 1 block up is Chestnut Street. Chestnut is the heart of the Marina district with fabulous restaurants, more shopping, movie theaters, and fitness gyms/studios.

If walking, biking or running is your exercise of choice, a short 15 minute walk north will lead you to the Bay. You can walk all along the waterfront to Crissy Field and the Golden Gate Bridge. Or, head south to Pacific Heights and Japantown and go west to check out the Presidio green space and smell the eucalyptus trees. You can even walk or take a short bus ride to North Beach for gelato and espresso.

neighborhood_overview:
We are right in the middle of San Francisco in the historic North of Panhandle ("NOPA") neighborhood, near Presidio Heights, and accessible to everything this great city has to offer. The area is very clean and safe, quiet at night and thriving during the day. Walk among Victorian gems, soak in the cafe and foodie scene, bike to the beaches or the Mission, or take a cab or easy bus to anywhere. Stroll to these unique neighborhood attractions, all within a few blocks:
* Alamo Square's Painted Ladies ("The 7 Sisters")
* Panhandle Park to Golden Gate Park
* Amazing restaurants: NOPA (New American), Che Fico (Italian), Bar Vale (Spanish), Ragazza Pizza, Crudo (seafood), Nopalito, Tsunami Sushi, Souvla, (Greek)
* Cafe paradise: Matching Half, The Mill, Bob's Donuts, Peet's
* Wine/bar heaven: Wine Kitchen, Vinyl, Fly, Horse Feather, Fools Errand
* Gourmet food to go: Faletti's, Bi-Rite Divis
* Farmer's market: Sunday 10-2 four blocks away
* Enter

description:
Explore San Francisco from this spacious 1 bedroom, 1 bath apt centrally located on the sunny hilltop of Mount Olympus. Easy downhill access to public transportation. Full kitchen, private balcony and, of course, Stunning Views!

The space
Enter the building through a common entrance; go down two flights of stairs through your private entrance to a sunny, light-filled retreat space with panoramic southeast views. This fully furnished unit is tastefully decorated in a colorful, contemporary style with all the comforts of home.

The Living Space: Enter the front door to an open living space with a kitchen, bistro table and barstools, dining and living room to the sliding glass door that leads to a private balcony that looks out to the bay.

The updated kitchen is fully furnished with new stainless appliances and kitchenware. There are several grocery stores nearby if you want to cook, and of course, lots of great places to eat out or order in
neighborhood_overview: Mt. Olympus is a quiet, hidden gem in San Francisco, almost a secret neighborhood. It is easily accessible to green space and all parts of the City by public transportation or a short walk. We love the views and the quiet, park-like setting.
host_about:
Greg and I have lived in San Francisco for over 25 years and have enjoyed exploring our own "backyard" to learn about its many treasures. We have no children, but are pet parents to a handsome Jack Russell Terrier named Grady who rules our world. Both of us are retired after long careers and now spend our time having fun with friends and family. We both play golf (Greg more than Deb) and ride bikes (Deb more than Greg). We love good food, good coffee, and good wine; all found within a short distance of our place. We both enjoy hiking the City's green spaces and neighborhood haunts to explore the treasures of San Francisco. We love sharing our favorite spots with our guests.  

Among our favorite destinations are Kauai, New Orleans, Charleston, New York, the District of Columbia, the Oregon Coast and Seattle.

neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood is safe, beautiful and greatly located in the city San Francisco. We face the Pacific ocean in a very low key awesome neighborhood. People can walk in our streets at any time, day or night without problems, however it is extremely foggy in summers and cold so consider this prior booking our home. It is a quiet area and we expect you to respect that.
It is against our privacy measures to be waiting with luggage in front of our home, to ensure this, we expect you to text us 10 minutes prior to your arrival and we will be ready for you. host_about:
I am delighted to share my home and wholeheartedly welcome people that honor their word when they agree to my house-rules prior booking. COVID chaotic guests disrupting our lives terribly made us suffer more than enough. I speak with ten years experience. Prior COVID I have served breakfast and dinner every day and I am sad that I can’t do it anymore but the heart the love and the overall integrity is intact. 
If you know few things about Lebanese people, as I am one, family, values, generosity, insecurity, our priorities in our lives. That is what you will have in my home, a precious place that I have been living and growing with my children and hundreds of plants and trees for the last 29 years❤️
We all live great lives, I am a designer/manufacturer working in China since the 90s so it makes it impossible  to continue easily when anyone with special needs or hotel mentality book our bedrooms. Please make sure to understand that I run an extremely tight ship and have eyes on every detail. We attend all matters immediately not only caring for all and everything but to make sure that issues are stoped before they begin.
Our home and neighborhood are extremely safe and as a designer with three amazingly gifted hard working adult children, we have designed this Jungle/Museum/Doll House and sanctuary. Clean air and environment, clean bathrooms and bedrooms are what awaits you, so welcome and enjoy these walls that express what I envision in my heart and soul as beautiful, all blending with art from different countries and periods in history, plants and colors❤️ 

We are super blessed and protected by a team of four fantastic Christian humans that work for us and help us keep it all magnificently well and clean for over sixteen years, that trust and security is PRICELESS and if it is the Lord’s will, it will be yours too.
Our home faces the Pacific Ocean, about 50 blocks away and when it is not foggy, our sunsets are dream-like! That said, the fog crawls up from the ocean and literally sits on top of our homes and neighborhood most of the time, specially during the summer, thus, I cannot express enough the importance the travel accordingly.
There will probably be other guests like you during your stay so we ask to whisper between 8 PM and 10 in the morning and if you’re going to be on the phone, you absolutely have to wear your headphones. Equally important is to notice that to enjoy good internet, as we all work online, we will ask that you choose ONE device for Wifi access. 

In order to keep control of all details, my children and I personally are constantly here to help, explain and be of any assistance to you all, so to be informed of any and all needs you might have: we WILL TRULY do our maximum to accommodate you so always let US KNOW what you need, please!

In as much as the prices in our listings are concerned, we are happy to offer a rate that is at least 60% off in comparison to our  neighbors because we are blessed enough so love to share!

I, the lucky mom and house owner, Lulu, speak eight languages, studying my ninth now and I am fortunate enough to travel around the world for business.

We look forward to sharing our lives with y’all! 
FYI, I go by “MamaLu” but my very favorite nickname is the “Creature From The Forest” :D
Welcome!
MamaLu

neighborhood_overview:
The Inner Mission District- "La Mision" is a great place to land in SF because of it's central location & close access to downtown.
It is the city's Latino district & has been the gateway for most new immigrants, initially Italian, Irish, then predominantly Latino since the 1960's , more recent arrivals are the artists, hipsters & even more recent, the techies.
The community is famous for its historic buildings, Mission burritos (the best in the US), grungy artistic scene, it's colorful murals & political organizing.
The neighborhood has a continued history of immigrant rights & before that the Chicano civil rights movement of the 1960's. In spite of all the recent gentrification the community is still 48% Latino.
Though the Mission still retains it's gritty 'barrio' (hood) flavor the neighborhood has been undergoing a second wave of gentrification though I think there is still plenty of SF soul left to go around, maybe now you just have to know where to
host_about:
Hola! 
I love to travel, the last place I went was the Caribbean in Honduras (awesome) &  I have been day dreaming about my next destination-Colombia.  I also love to dance-all kinds but Samba is my religion!
For an authentically Mission experience there is a free Salsa lesson included in your stay- I can teach you in 15 mins -yes  it's that easy or well,  just enough to fake the rest...
I also love gardening, culture, fashion, camping, history and living in SF.
For 23 years, I owned one of the last Latin cultural stores in the community, it was a landmark legacy business which gave me a very intimate & spiritual connection to the Mission- hence why I  was  picked to film an Airbnb success story commercial you may have seen on u-tube called 
"Airbnb Nancy" - what a blast! 
 I love showing guests the best of SF life, here are some of the best things to do beyond the touristy sights: 
-Bike along the embarcadero, across the GG bridge & take the ferry back from Sausalito- epic! 
bring some Napa or Sonoma Chardonnay with you &  on the  way stop at a crab stand at Fisherman's Wharf to pick up a very affordable crab sandwich on sourdough for the Quintessential San Francisco meal- have a picnic at Aquatic Park or Chrissy Field. 
-Hike Lands End 
-People watch at Dolores Park - best sunset view is at 20th & Church-don’t miss the irreverent Hunky Jesus (look a like) contest on Easter Sunday 
-Catch some blues at The Saloon in North Beach Sunday night 
-Eat a burrito in the Mission, Best in the US & do a self guided mural walk thru Balmy Alley & around. 
-Eat Dim Sum in Chinatown 
at the Hang ah Tea House & stop by The Fortune Cookie Factory nearby, (invented by a Japanese man)
- Eat buffalo stew or burger at historical Tommy’s Joint & be transported back to the days of the Barbary Coast 
-ok The Cheese Cake Factory above Macy's Union Square can be a bit new money & a little touristy, but the food is actually pretty good & the view is AMAZING
-The museum on the 2nd story of the Boudin Bakery in Fishermans Wharf is a little gem & you can see how the bread is being made into turtles, dolphons, crabs & other adorable animals.  After that head to Musee Mecanique a few doors away for antique arcade machines, relics left from Playland that used to be at Ocean Beach.
-Play "I left my Heart in San Francisco" by Tony Bennett & read some Herb Caen, who coined the term "Baghdad by the Bay" 
-Have some coffee at Caffe Trieste in North Beach, where  the 1st Capuccino in the West was served  & also where Francis Ford Coppola wrote The God Father.
- See the Zapatista Mural in Jack Kerouc Alley, painted by a dear friend &  behind iconic City Lights Bookstore .  Ask me about the mural story.
-Catch a baseball game at Oracle park !
SF songs & bands : 
City Lights by Journey
The Grateful Dead of course
Huey Lewis & the News 
Carlos Santana  & more !

You can also see the guide I made for Airbnb's  Mission Institutions:
https://www.airbnb.com/things-to-do/insider-guidebook/108?location=San%20Francisco%2C%20CA%2C%20United%20States&source=&currentTab=place_tab

...p.s. once you know Salsa you also know Cumbia, Merengue, Bachata...

The Inner Richmond is a charming and diverse neighborhood, known for great Asian food, and craft beer breweries. There are great bars and restaurants on Clement St, Balboa St and Geary Blvd, but it is generally quiet at night. A great place to relax after a busy day seeing the city! neighborhood_overview:
The Potrero Hill district is one of the most unique neighborhoods in San Francisco and has gone through several changes from working class to the newer family oriented direction since the 1990's

Potrero Hill is one of the sunniest neighborhoods in San Francisco. It is insulated from our famous fog and chill from the ocean and gives some of the most spectacular views of downtown and the bay bridge. If you are up for a few hills it can be a great walking experience and the ever growing "hub" of 18th street is always a great place to start a day.

One of the best parts of Potrero Hill is that it is a neighborhood further from the "hustle and bustle" so it has a quiet and sleepy feel but you are never more than a few minutes from the fray.

Giving new people an opportunity to experience San Francisco is what we hope to do as hosts.  One of us was born in San Francisco (the other in Miami) and think there are a ton of fantastic things to experience here while on your stay either for work or fun :)

We hope that people have a fun and relaxing stay but mostly are happy!

host_about: My wife and I have lived in San Francisco for 40 years; prior to this, we lived in the Los Angeles area for nearly 10 years. I am originally from Hungary. I left when I was 16 in 1956. neighborhood_overview:
If there's any area of San Francisco that evokes images of the long-gone '60s hippie culture, the Haight is it. Fragments of that flower-power, incense-burning, acid-dropping, tie-dye-wearing, peace-and-love-vibing era can be purchased at smoke shops and Eastern-influenced outlets bearing names like Dreams of Kathmandu and The Love of Ganesha. But save for a few hippie relics, the Haight today is a whole new scene. Exclusive boutiques, high-end vintage-clothing shops, second-hand stores, Internet cafés and hip restaurants have all settled in, making the Haight one of San Francisco's commercial centers.

Neo-punks, club kids, fashionites, tourists and neighborhood folks are equally at home here, whether they have come to get a new piercing, grab a burrito, find the latest drum 'n' bass 12-inch or just people-watch from a café. But there are two distinctly different areas of the Haight: The Upper Haight, which stretches from Stanyan to Masonic, is the more moneyed shopping zone

Divisadero street has (1/2 block) many unique shops, specialty food stores, bars and restaurants, that are all within walking distance. The entrance to Golden Gate Park, aka the Panhandle, is located 2 blocks away, and the Castro, as well as the Upper and Lower Haight, are within walking distance. If you drive a car, the free app SPOTANGELS is worth checking out. There's plenty of public transport near by.

Alamo Square Park, the neighborhood's focal point and namesake, consists of four city blocks at the top of a hill overlooking much of downtown San Francisco, with a number of large and architecturally distinctive mansions along the perimeter, including the "Painted Ladies", a well-known postcard motif. neighborhood_overview: The Sunset is a unique demographic of surfers, dog lovers, and beach-goers. Typically the Sunset is foggy for June and July, but is clear most other days of the year.  Typical yearly temperatures hover in the 60-65 degrees Fahrenheit.  Our neighborhood is a friendly community, where most of us know each other by name and many natives still live in the area. The sunset district is like the "suburbs of the City", making it a more relaxed environment with all the benefits of a big city and entertainment at your fingertips.  Golden Gate Park (GGP) is within walking distance (1 mile) and holds the Outside Lands concert and the Hardly Strictly Bluegrass Festival. GGP also has the Academy of Science museum, De Young art museum, and Japanese Tea Garden. The Great Highway offers a beautiful 5 mile walking path from Sloat ave. to the Cliff House/Sutro Baths.  It is great for running, biking, walking. Popular restaurants include: Thanh Long, Outerlands, Cliff House, Beach Chalet & Brewery, Celia'
host_about: We are native San Franciscans, work full time, enjoy the outdoors, camping, the beach, and enjoy wine with friends and family. I am particularly clean and love a comfortable home to relax in.  With roots from Hawaii, we try to live by the spirit of Aloha and the virtue of being honest and genuine with others.  We have traveled to exotic places around the world, including Bali, Costa Rica, Europe, Canada, Mexico, Japan and have visited over 20 U.S. states.  We love meeting new people and sharing our city life. Our lives are revolved around our children and raising a stable family in this fast paced city.  We frequent Lake Tahoe for skiing and snowboarding and Hawaii in the summer to visit family. Ocean beach is our front yard and is our haven for an extra breath. Constantly learning how to simplify and enjoy life is a focus.

neighborhood_overview:
LOVELY LOCATION: FUN, INTERESTING, HISTORIC
* Telegraph Hill the most beautiful of San Francisco’s Hills. Intimate and delightful. Possibly also the USA's most famous hill
* One block to the lively cafes, restaurants, bars of North Beach, yet quiet
* Oldest part of San Francisco, part of pre-Gold Rush Yerba Buena
* Rebuilt after 1906 earthquake
* Telegraph Hill got name from pole-and-arm signal station, precursor of internet
* Nearby Coit Tower has perhaps the greatest of urban vistas anywhere
* Delightful, quirky gardens of Greenwich and Filbert streets adjacent, containing half the few buildings that survived 1906 earthquake and fire
* Fog enshrouds the hill at night and morning, burns off revealing brilliant sun and blue skies (summer)
* Adjacent to Barbary Coast, former red light district of late 1800s, containing remaining buildings to escape 1906 earthquake and fire
* Beatnik movement centered here, in Caffe Trieste, Vesuv
